I can appreciate a well-engineered recording played through nice equipment.

I never said your were "professional" I just said you fit in with the most professional-writers relative to what we had. The main reason is how well you can set up scenes and progress them in you short/medium size stories:

>A Man and a Beast
>Space Croc
>Bangaa Thing (requires FF pre-knowledge)
>Little Drop of Poison

You seem to have problems with longer stories, sometimes over explaining things unlike your shorter stories. When you describe a scene you don't parcel it out, instead the mood change, dialogue, and setting all meld into one.

"Moans of pain woke me with a start. Rosa was on the floor, huddled in a fetal position, crying out about her bones shifting once more. Her spine jutted out slightly, and I could see the individual vertebrae moving to new positions, causing her body to become even larger. Ribs changed size, opening up, almost threatening to pierce through skin.

My sweet did not leave the bedroom that day"

>Man woke up to the sound of screaming
>He looked on the floor to see is wife transforming even more
>it looked painful
>Despite this I still see her as my sweet wife
>I know she is my sweet wife still and she will not leave the bedroom due to the physical and emotional toll this transformation is having on her
>I hope she is alright

All that explained fluently in your passage. No dialogue, No explaining through the protag 5 senses. Just raw exposition. Something I wish I could do.

T. Deco

>>28986833
Storytelling is an almost completely different skillset close as I can tell. There is plenty of hard, learnable and teachable technique to both skills, but I am certainly a much better poet than I am a storyteller. I figure that's because I, like most of us, was trained to write essays orders of magnitude more than I was stories. I'm good at that structure and can speak concisely in it. Creatively speaking, however, I picked up most of my language and structure from reading and, perhaps more significantly, being read to. I learned a lot about what I loved the sound and feel of, but, for whatever reason, not as much about why I loved the story. As such, I tend to lapse into overdescription and lose track of how much attention I pay to individual scenes and events, and suffer poor pacing even if I'm confident in the core of the plot. Degeneracy Pressure is an exception to this and I'm by far the most proud of it as a result, but I Degeneracy Pressure was very deliberate and measured. In Silver Lining I just ran with a fancy, and while I am confident in the core of the story, I'll be the first to admit that the execution as it stands is fucking boring. Meanwhile, there have been plenty of stories here that I've eagerly read and awaited updates for that I never even noticed had grammar issues or sentence structure I didn't care for until somebody else pointed it out. It is entirely possible to tell a wonderful story with barely any command of language as long as you can get your point across. It's also entirely possible to write a whole lot of beautiful nothing. The best manuscripts have both, but as a reader, I'd usually rather read a good story with serviceable language than a boring one with excellent language. There's nothing for either situation except practice with the other.
